\section{Ferromagnetism and Charge Order from a Frozen Electron Configuration in Strained Epitaxial LaCoO_\{3\}}
 Kim, and P. J. RyanPhys. Rev. Lett. 120, 197201 - Published 8 May 2018

DOI: 10.1103/PhysRevLett.120.197201

\section*{Ferromagnetism and Charge Order from a Frozen Electron Configuration in Strained Epitaxial $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$ }
(Dated: March 14, 2018)

\begin{abstract}
We report order of the cobalt electron configuration in ferromagnetic strained epitaxial $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$. Specifically, the presence of charge order is demonstrated from distinct features of the resonant cobalt contribution to superstructure reflections. Density functional theory calculations show the observed order is consistent with the spin-state periodicity predicted to give rise to ferromagnetism in $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$. Through modification of symmetry by strain, concurrent frozen charge and spin-state order are stabilized, giving rise to long range magnetic order.
\end{abstract}

Correlated electron physics is heavily dependent upon interplay between physical parameters such as spin, charge, and lattice. Due to coupling between these parameters, subtle changes in one can lead to significant and unexpected changes in another $[1,2]$. For instance, lattice distortions can dramatically alter the properties of materials with correlated electrons, such as $\mathrm{La}_{1-x} \mathrm{Sr}_{x} \mathrm{MnO}_{3}$, which can be driven from metal to insulator and ferromagnet to antiferromagnet via epitaxial strain [3]. Subtle lattice distortions can also give rise to ferromagnetism in a paramagnet, as found in $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$, which becomes ferromagnetic under tensile strain $[4,5]$. While recent studies have demonstrated that a straininduced increase in the average Co-O bond length, i.e. an increase in the oxygen octahedral volume, is critical to the appearance of ferromagnetism [6, 7], the exact nature of the microscopic mechanism by which lattice couples to spin is unclear, and several models of the atomic characteristics and magnetic exchange that give rise to ferromagnetism in $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$ have been proposed [8-14].

Bulk $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$ is rhombohedral with pseudocubiclattice parameters of $3.830 \AA$ and $90.7^{\circ}$ (Fig. 1(a)) [1517 ; ; it is a nonmagnetic insulator below $110 \mathrm{~K}$, a paramagnetic semiconductor between 110 and $500 \mathrm{~K}$, and a paramagnetic metal above $500 \mathrm{~K}$. In the nonmagnetic phase, all $\mathrm{Co}^{3+}$ ions are in the low spin (LS) $t_{2 g}^{6} e_{g}^{0}$ state, and higher-temperature phase transitions result from changes in the $\mathrm{Co}^{3+}$ spin state to intermediate spin (IS) $t_{2 g}^{5} e_{g}^{1}$ and/or high spin (HS) $t_{2 g}^{4} e_{g}^{2}$ configurations (Fig. 1(b)) [18]. Though the details of the spin states present in the paramagnetic phases of $\mathrm{LaCoO}_{3}$ are debated, one possible model supported by experiment $[18,19]$ and theory [20-23] implicates a mixture of LS and HS $\mathrm{Co}^{3+}$ as responsible for the paramagnetic semiconducting phase up to $350 \mathrm{~K}$. In this model, thermally-driven cooperative oxygen displacements cause formation of two Co sites ordered in a rocksalt-type ar-

