film reflections (Figs. 2(f-g, i)). From the distance between satellites, the period of the modulation is determined to be $\sim 28 \mathrm{~nm}$. Scattering at the $(00 l)$ reflections is only sensitive to changes in the vertical separation between atoms, i.e. in the direction of the substrate $c$-axis $\left(\hat{\mathbf{c}}_{\mathbf{0}}\right)$. Thus transverse atomic displacements give rise to the lattice modulation. This is consistent with other reports of lattice modulations in oxide thin films [36, 37]. Additionally, the half-order superstructure $\left(\frac{1}{2} \frac{\overline{3}}{2} \frac{5}{2}\right)$ film reflection exhibits satellites with in-plane momentum transfer identical to that of the (00l) film\\
